          "body": "Verse 11 is the psalm's tragic hinge: 'But My people did not listen to My voice, and Israel did not obey Me.' The adversative 'but' carries enormous weight — everything God offered in verses 6-10 crashes into Israel's refusal. The failure is described in both receptive and active terms: they did not listen (a posture of reception) and did not obey (a posture of action). Verse 12 names the consequence: 'So I gave them over to the stubbornness of their heart, to walk in their own devices.' The verb 'gave them over' (shalach) is judicial — God releases Israel to the very direction they have insisted on choosing. This is not passive neglect but active withdrawal of restraint. The phrase 'stubbornness of their heart' (sherirut lev) is Jeremiah's diagnostic word for the unreformed Israelite heart (Jeremiah 3:17; 7:24; 9:14). Walking in their own devices (moetsah) is the psalm's darkest image: a people navigating by self-generated counsel rather than divine word."
