        "body": "The divine oracle's demand in verses 8-10 is structurally a restatement of Exodus 20:1-3 — the first and greatest commandment. 'Let there be no strange god among you; nor shall you worship any foreign god' (81:9) is not a general religious warning but a covenant prohibition rooted in the specific relationship established in verse 10: 'I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you up from the land of Egypt.' The Exodus is not past history; it is present identity. God's exclusive claim on Israel's worship is grounded in His exclusive act of Israel's redemption.\n\nThe word 'strange' (*zur*, v.9) and 'foreign' (*nekhar*, v.9) together cover both the gods of neighboring nations (politically foreign) and any deity outside the covenant relationship (covenantally strange). The false teachers in Asaph's context — and throughout Israel's monarchic period — were not asking Israel to abandon Yahweh entirely but to supplement Him: Baal for the rain, Asherah for the harvest, Yahweh for the festivals. Psalm 81 refuses the supplement. The first commandment allows no division of the divine portfolio.\n\nVerse 10 closes with an image that has no parallel in the Ancient Near East: 'Open your mouth wide and I will fill it.' Most ancient religions required elaborate human provision — sacrifice, ritual preparation, payment — to secure divine blessing. Psalm 81 pictures the opposite posture: the open, empty, dependent mouth. The image is of a baby bird, or of the poor who have nothing to bring. Charles Spurgeon commented on this verse: 'The wider we open our mouths in prayer and expectation, the more God will fill them. He is not straitened, but we are straitened in ourselves.' The tragedy of verse 11 is not that God withheld; it is that Israel chose a closed mouth over an open one.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The preamble structure 'I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you out of Egypt' (*ani Yehovah Eloheicha asher heleticha me-erets Mitsrayim*) is verbatim Exodus 20:2 — the Decalogue's ground clause. *Zur* (strange) and *nekhar* (foreign) are the two standard OT terms for what is outside the covenant. *Peh* (mouth, v.10) is the word for both the physical mouth and speech — the open mouth is the posture of both dependence and declaration."
